description:
Many mosquito larvae floating in a cattle water trough, elevation 871 feet. When startled, they quickly wiggled themselves down to the bottom.

Cold Weather Mosquito (Culiseta incidens) are winged, biting insects in the Mosquitoes (Culicidae) family. Some mosquitoes are vectors of various diseases (like Malaria in tropical habitats). 
Cold Weather Mosquito Larvae live in the water and pass through four growth stages. They come to the surface to breathe through a siphon tube that they also used to hang from the waters surface. The larva feed on microorganisms and organic matter in the water. Adult Cool-weather Mosquito is a common domestic species, most abundant during the cooler seasons, when they bite people (and other mammals) readily. It breeds in a variety of natural ground waters, like ditches, clear pools, swamps, and artificial containers, like rain barrels, old tires, and water troughs. They are common throughout the state of California.
Larva have a pair of conspicuous hair tufts near the base of the posterior breathing tube.
Pupa have two respiratory trumpets emerging from a combined head and thorax that poke through the water’s surface to breathe air.

Field Guide to California Insects, by Kip Will, J. Gross, D. Rubinoff , J. Powell, 2nd ed., 2020, pp. 279-281. Figs. 405-409.
